00:00:05,403 --> 00:00:09,216
Welcome back to the course 
on plasma physics and applications.

2
00:00:09,216 --> 00:00:12,213
In the last module,
we have learned the fundamentals

3
00:00:12,213 --> 00:00:14,184
of magnetic reconnection.

4
00:00:14,184 --> 00:00:17,042
Through this process, a large fraction
of magnetic energy

5
00:00:17,042 --> 00:00:20,263
goes into particle acceleration
and plasma heating.

6
00:00:20,263 --> 00:00:25,275
Magnetic reconnection is probably
one of the most important mechanisms

7
00:00:25,275 --> 00:00:28,515
that heats the solar corona
at a temperature of the order

8
00:00:28,515 --> 00:00:30,731
of one million degrees Kelvin.

9
00:00:30,731 --> 00:00:33,884
Magnetic reconnection also plays
a fundamental role

10
00:00:33,884 --> 00:00:39,133
during coronal mass ejections
which release a huge amount of energy

11
00:00:39,133 --> 00:00:41,203
and plasma from the Sun.

12
00:00:41,203 --> 00:00:44,760
In this module, which is the last module
in Plasma Astrophysics,

13
00:00:44,760 --> 00:00:50,076
I will describe how from a hot plasma
atmosphere, the solar wind can blow.

14
00:00:50,076 --> 00:00:54,330
We will use a simple MHD description
to derive estimates

15
00:00:54,330 --> 00:00:58,726
of the solar wind speed and we will see
how the solar wind can shape

16
00:00:58,726 --> 00:01:01,212
the magnetosphere around the earth.

17
00:01:02,653 --> 00:01:08,270
The first hints of the solar wind
came in the early 19th century

18
00:01:08,270 --> 00:01:13,102
when Birkeland suggested
that a continuous particle emission

19
00:01:13,102 --> 00:01:15,162
was coming from sunspots.

20
00:01:15,162 --> 00:01:18,933
This was to explain
the observed correlation

21
00:01:18,933 --> 00:01:21,749
between auroras and sunspots.

22
00:01:22,543 --> 00:01:26,631
About 30 years later, Chapman
and Ferraro suggested

23
00:01:26,631 --> 00:01:32,090
that particles were emitted from the Sun
only during solar flares

24
00:01:32,090 --> 00:01:37,805
and otherwise the space
between the Sun and the earth was empty.

25
00:01:38,836 --> 00:01:43,883
The first real evidence of the solar wind
came from comet tails.

26
00:01:44,310 --> 00:01:49,473
In 1951, Bierman observed
that the cometary tails

27
00:01:49,473 --> 00:01:54,722
point directly away from the Sun
regardless of the comet's velocity.

28
00:01:55,514 --> 00:01:59,508
It conjectured that
this must be due to ionized gas

29
00:01:59,508 --> 00:02:01,689
pushed away by the solar wind.

30
00:02:02,568 --> 00:02:08,022
An example is given by this picture here
that shows the comet <i>Hale-Bopp</i>,

31
00:02:08,022 --> 00:02:11,742
viewed from Los Alamos
in New Mexico, U.S.A.

32
00:02:13,147 --> 00:02:16,994
As you can see,
the comet has two distinct tails.

33
00:02:17,738 --> 00:02:23,339
The white tail is a dust tail driven
by light pressure

34
00:02:23,339 --> 00:02:25,424
and it points away from the sun.

35
00:02:26,383 --> 00:02:31,739
The blue tail instead is an ion tail
which is driven by the solar wind.

36
00:02:32,980 --> 00:02:35,929
It is not radial with respect to the Sun,

37
00:02:36,924 --> 00:02:41,739
as the comet has about one tenth
of the speed of the solar wind.

38
00:02:41,749 --> 00:02:45,896
The first measurement of the solar wind
came from the <i>Mariner 2</i> mission

39
00:02:45,896 --> 00:02:50,636
that was launched
on the 27th of August, 1962.

40
00:02:51,733 --> 00:02:57,364
The Mariner 2 provided three months
of continuous solar wind data

41
00:02:57,364 --> 00:03:00,065
while traveling towards Venus.

42
00:03:00,732 --> 00:03:08,002
It measured solar wind speed
between 300 and 700 km/s.

43
00:03:09,403 --> 00:03:15,157
This was the first experimental proof
of the existence of the solar wind.

44
00:03:16,721 --> 00:03:22,392
More recent data has been provided
by the joint ESA-NASA mission

45
00:03:22,392 --> 00:03:27,349
<i>Ulysses</i>, that was launched
on the 6th of October, 1990.

46
00:03:28,093 --> 00:03:33,290
As shown in this picture,
Ulysses was launched towards Jupiter,

47
00:03:33,290 --> 00:03:37,779
where using the slingshot effect
provided by gravity,

48
00:03:37,779 --> 00:03:41,529
it entered a polar orbit around the Sun.

49
00:03:42,660 --> 00:03:46,493
Ulysses performed
three sets of polar passes.

50
00:03:47,171 --> 00:03:52,949
The radial plots shown here show
the solar wind speed combined data

51
00:03:53,487 --> 00:03:58,260
from all three of Ulysses's
polar orbits of the Sun,

52
00:03:58,260 --> 00:04:02,428
each of which takes approximately
six years to complete.

53
00:04:03,396 --> 00:04:09,651
Ulysses was equipped with an instrument
called <i>SWOOPS</i>, that stands for:

54
00:04:09,651 --> 00:04:13,599
Solar Wind Observations
Over the Poles of the Sun.

55
00:04:14,957 --> 00:04:20,365
This instrument was designed to provide 
measurements of the solar wind speeds.

56
00:04:22,741 --> 00:04:29,108
The first orbit occurred
during a period of solar minimum

57
00:04:29,108 --> 00:04:32,667
as indicated by the sunspot number.

58
00:04:35,082 --> 00:04:39,486
Ulysses measured a slow wind
over the Equator,

59
00:04:41,765 --> 00:04:46,091
of the order of 200 km/s,

60
00:04:46,091 --> 00:04:53,989
and fast wind over the poles of the Sun,

61
00:04:54,754 --> 00:04:58,496
of the order of 700 km/s.

62
00:04:59,526 --> 00:05:06,850
The second orbit of Ulysses corresponded
to a period of maximum activity

63
00:05:06,850 --> 00:05:13,382
as shown by the sunspot number here,
between 1998 and 2004.

64
00:05:14,489 --> 00:05:18,422
During the second pass,
fast and slow winds were measured

65
00:05:18,422 --> 00:05:23,072
at all latitudes consistent
with a solar maximum activity.

66
00:05:24,079 --> 00:05:28,936
Ulysses then completed
more than 3/4 of the third orbit,

67
00:05:28,936 --> 00:05:34,174
as you can see here,
occurring around the solar minimum cycle.

68
00:05:35,376 --> 00:05:37,301
During this last cycle,

69
00:05:38,206 --> 00:05:41,576
Ulysses also gathered information

70
00:05:41,576 --> 00:05:46,952
indicating that the solar wind
was about 25% less powerful

71
00:05:46,952 --> 00:05:49,782
than it was in the previous
solar minimum cycle.

72
00:05:50,893 --> 00:05:54,325
So far, we have reviewed
experimental data of the solar wind.

73
